**Prime Number Checker Function**
=====================================

The following JavaScript function checks whether a given number is prime. A prime number is a natural number greater than 1 that has no positive divisors other than 1 and itself.

```javascript
/**
 * Checks whether a given number is prime.
 *
 * @param {number} num - The number to check for primality.
 * @returns {boolean} True if the number is prime, false otherwise.
 */
function isPrime(num) {
  // Edge cases: numbers less than 2 are not prime
  if (num < 2) {
    return false;
  }

  // 2 is the only even prime number
  if (num === 2) {
    return true;
  }

  // All other even numbers are not prime
  if (num % 2 === 0) {
    return false;
  }

  // Check odd factors up to the square root of num
  for (let i = 3; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i += 2) {
    if (num % i === 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }

  // If no factors are found, the number is prime
  return true;
}
```

**Example Use Cases**
--------------------

```javascript
console.log(isPrime(25)); // false
console.log(isPrime(23)); // true
console.log(isPrime(37)); // true
console.log(isPrime(48)); // false
```

This function uses a simple trial division method to check for primality. It first handles edge cases (numbers less than 2), then checks for even numbers (all of which are not prime except for 2). Finally, it checks odd factors up to the square root of the number, as any factor larger than the square root would have a corresponding factor smaller than the square root. If no factors are found, the number is prime.
